I think that's the right approach. Don't try to replace all the mock resolvers at once. Start with the root Query and Mutation resolvers, because they are the simplest. The nested resolvers (User.posts, Post.author, Comment.post, etc.) depend on relationships and require a bit more thought.

I'd implement them in this order:

Phase 1: Root Queries ✅ (Easy)
Query.Users
Query.User

Query.Posts
Query.Post

These are just:

Resolver
    ↓
Service
    ↓
Repository
    ↓
Mapper

No nested lookups.

Phase 2: Root Mutations ✅ (Easy)
Mutation.CreateUser
Mutation.CreatePost
Mutation.CreateComment

Flow:

GraphQL Input
        ↓
Mapper
        ↓
Entity
        ↓
Service
        ↓
Repository
        ↓
Database
        ↓
Entity
        ↓
Mapper
        ↓
GraphQL Model

Again, straightforward.

Phase 3: User Nested Resolvers ⭐
User.posts
User.comments

Both are simple foreign-key lookups.

user.ID
     ↓
PostService.GetByUserID()

or

CommentService.GetByUserID()
Phase 4: Post Nested Resolvers ⭐⭐
Post.author
Post.comments

Again, direct lookups.

post.UserID
        ↓
UserService.GetByID()

post.ID
      ↓
CommentService.GetByPostID()
Phase 5: Comment Nested Resolvers ⭐⭐⭐
Comment.author
Comment.post

These are the ones we discussed—they require access to UserID and PostID on the GraphQL model (or another strategy to carry those foreign keys).